And my focus is on women in their 40s and beyond.  What you need to THRIVE with fluctuating hormones, stress, body composition goals, digestive woes and more.  And guess what, this involves more PLANTS!  Easily absorbable protein, fiber and healthy fats to the rescue.

What does Plant-Powered actually mean? 

▶️ Plant-based Diet:  Focusing on whole foods, minimally processed derived from plants, including vegetables, greens, whole grains, nuts, seeds, legumes and fruits with few to no animal products. 

It can take many forms depending on your goals.  Examples: 
•	Meatless Monday
•	Certain Days of the Week Vegetarian/Vegan
•	Vegetarian – No meat/chicken/seafood, but including eggs and dairy
•	Vegan – No animal-based products
•	Variations of Above By Week/Day

HIGH NET-GAIN FOODS:		PLATFORM FOR LONG-TERM SUCCESS
➡️ More nutrient-dense and easily digested assimilated because in their natural state 
➡️ Reduce the stress response and allow the body to conserve rather than expend energy ➡️ Net-energy surplus = Extra energy, quick restoration of cells damaged by stress (exercise) and improved immune function

And this, guys, equates to:

•	Increased energy
•	Enhanced body composition
•	Improved mental clarity
•	Reduced cravings and insatiable hunger
•	Better sleep quality
•	Reduced cholesterol
•	Stronger bones
•	Better skin quality
•	Less joint inflammation
•	Faster recovery from fitness

And can I read your mind⁉️ You are thinking, "But where would I get my protein?!"

More to come on this...but short answer, "From where your animal-based protein gets THEIRS!" 🥦🥬🥕🥗

Bananas are seriously healthy for your heart. In case you are not aware, bananas are very rich in a mineral called potassium. It is an electrolyte that our body requires to keep electrical impulses flowing through the body. 
Without electrical impulses, our hearts will not operate.
So, eat bananas for a happy and healthy heart.

HELLO AND GOODPIE

Ingredients:
1 box of simple mills pizza dough
Kalamata Olives
Mushrooms
Mozarella/cheddar cheese or vegan cheese 
Handful of fresh basil
Raos pizza sauce 

Make and bake dough according to box instructions in a cast iron pan. In the meantime, chop your mushrooms, slice olives, and shred your cheese and cut basil. Once pizza dough is done cooking, layer tomato sauce, shredded cheese, basil, mushrooms, and olives. Return to oven and bake for another 15-20 minutes till bubbly. 

Serve with spicy ranch dipping sauce. AKA: ranch that makes you dance. Posted on the grid.

🥧Zucchini Cake🥧

Sometimes I struggle with adding enough vegetables to my meals. So I found a way to add some more of them. For example: you can use them while baking! Zucchinis in a cake make it more moist, delicious and healthy. And you can even make it with chocolate!🍫🍫
For the cake you need:
- 400 g grated zucchini
- 3 eggs
- 170 g raw cane sugar
- 3 tsp vanilla sugar
- 3 tsp baking powder
- 125 ml vegetable oil (I use rapeseed oil)
- 50 g unsweetened cocoa powder
- 300 g gluten free flour

First roll in the grated zucchinis in a kitchen towel and press till water comes out. Then beat the eggs with the raw cane sugar and vanilla sugar. Now add the other ingredients little by little.
At the end add the zucchini and stir them in the dough. Pour the dough into a cake tin laid out with baking paper. Bake in a preheated oven for 35-40 minutes at 180°C. Then turn onto a rack and leave to cool.

Vorgestern sind wir auf Kreta angekommen und haben uns direkt mal an einem unserer Lieblingsgerichte versucht: kretisches Briam. 
In unsere Version haben wir einfach mal alles gepackt, was wir gefunden haben: 
Karotten
Passierte Tomaten 
Gehackte Tomaten 
Okraschoten (sehr wichtig 😉)
Mais 
Zucchini 
Aubergine 
Lauch
Knoblauch

Das alles wird einfach zusammen in der Pfanne angebraten und wenn man will (und wir wollen!) serviert man dazu griechischen Orzo. 
Stay tuned, bald gibts auch nochmal ein Video dazu. 
•
Two days ago we arrived in Crete and directly tried out one of our favorite recipes: Cretan Briam. In our version we just packed everything we could find in our dish:
Carrots 
Strained tomatoes 
Chopped tomatoes 
Okra (very important 😉)
Corn 
Zucchini
Eggplant 
Leek
Garlic

Simply sautée everything in a frying pan and serve it with some orzo if you want (and we do!) stay tuned, there will be a video on this!

Right, this year I am going all out with the vegetable growing!!
Last year the vegetable growing was quite underwhelming; we had recently moved house so we didn't know where the best place to plant veggies in the garden was and we had a 5 month old baby. 

But, this year I'm on it! I love lists, so this tick sheet is perfect for me to track what and when I'm planting things. 

I've have loads of seeds left over and in date from last year so I don't need to buy much new. The only thing have bought are some seed potatoes. 

The weather has been glorious so far this weekend so I've planted as many seeds as I can indoors ready for transplanting outside once our vegetable growing areas is prepped. 

I have no idea what I'm doing by the way, but I wing it, and usually things turn out ok! I could spend ages reading up on how to grow things, but that is just not my style. 

Anyone else winging it at gardening?

GREEN SMOOTHIE WITH BROCCOLI

A super healthy green smoothie recipe with broccoli. Surprisingly good and refreshing healthy smoothie!

INGREDIENTS
1/2 cup broccoli
1 cup spinach
1 banana
1 apple
1 lemon
1 carrot

INSTRUCTIONS
Peel banana and lemon, wash, and chop the other ingredients.
Put everything in a blender and blend until smooth at high-speed.
Keep the smoothie in the fridge in an air-tight container and drink it throughout the day - as breakfast and at work at snack time.

Hummus Naan Wraps
4 pieces naan bread
1 cup hummus (I used roasted garlic)
4 cups greens (I used leaf lettuce)
4 T. feta cheese

Veggie Mixture:
1/2 cup cucumber, peeled and diced
1/2 cup red pepper, diced
1/2 cup red onion, diced
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, quartered
2T. olive oil
1 1/2 T red wine vinegar
1/2 tsp Italian seasoning
1/4 tsp salt
1/4 tsp pepper
1/8 tsp garlic powder
1/4 tsp honey (optional)

Mix together all the ingredients for the veggie mixture.
While you are mixing the veggies together, warm or toast your naan bread.
Spread 1/4 c. hummus on naan.
Top with lettuce, veggie mixture, and feta cheese.

Options: add shredded chicken or garbanzo/other beans.
Change up the flavor with different kinds of hummus!

What Should u Eat? If u have diabetes,  you should focus on eating lean protein, high fiber, less processed carbs, fruits and vegetables, low-fat dairy and healthy vegetable based fats such as avocado, nuts, canola oil or olive oil. You should also manage ur carbohydrate intake.
A diabetes diet simply means eating the healthiest foods in moderate amounts and sticking to regular mealtimes. A diabetes diet is a healthy-eating plan that's naturally rich in nutrients and low in fat and calories. Key elements are fruits, vegetables and whole grains.

Sprouting alfalfa seeds to make a how to demo for Aisling’s Health School.

Sprouts like alfalfa and sunflower contain all 8 essential amino acids which are needed for bone health and bone density.

A common question I get is where do you get your calcium for bones?

You don’t need dairy for bone health. Dairy is mucus forming, feeds viruses and pathogens and builds up obstruction in your body over time.

For bone health focus on sprouts and plant rich sources of silica like celery juice, cucumbers, melons, artichokes, asparagus, dandelion, and leafy greens. There are also healing herbs that offer rich sources of silica including nettle leaf, horsetail, oatstraw, and rose hips. 🌿 

Magnesium is also needed for strong bones and blood sugar balance as it puts the calcium in the right place in your bones and blood sugars. A good magnesium supplement can be a game changer for your health. 

Focus on adding in foods that cleanse your body and eliminating foods that obstruct your body. What you focus on grows so focus on adding goodness.

Bloat... we’ve all been there! Check out this post from @bodysmartfitness on how you can beat the bloat.

🎈Beat the bloat!  🎈
 
🤰Bloating can put us in a right downer. It can derail our mood and make us feel like our efforts are going to waste. But could there be a reason why it's happening and could you combat it with these simple steps?  
 
🍽 Eat Smaller Meals  
Are your portions too big and your digestive system is struggling to cope? Try smaller portions and also be mindful of your eating speed to reduce that bloat.  
 
🥦 Cook your veggies don't eat them raw  
Raw vegetables can cause bloating for some people as they take longer to break down and have more bacteria on the surface.  
 
🥘 Make sure your fibre is in check   
Are you eating enough fibre and helping your digestive system along? Get more fibre in your diet by eating things like cruciferous vegetables, rice, berries and beans.  
 
💊 Probiotics & digestive enzymes  
You can get these in supplement format and they help with digestion.  
 
🍵 Drink hot water - tea - peppermint tea  
Soothing teas are always great for settling your stomach. We recommend peppermint teas and herbal teas. Try to go caffeine-free if possible.  
 
💧Get a sweat on  
Go and workout and get that bloat down! Get your blood pumping and help your body process properly.  
 
😧 Check for food sensitivities  
There could be an underlying intolerance or food sensitivity causing the bloat. Speak to your doctor or use a food diary to track symptoms and see patterns.

.

Eve’s plant nursery is in full swing! Pretty sure I’ve solidified my status of the crazy plant lady of the neighbourhood as every other person seems to glance at the windows. Spent the morning and early afternoon sowing and potting up. This week was time for tomatoes and cucumbers, as well as beetroot and a whole long list of brassicas. I ended up sowing a dozen different tomato varieties 🤗 A week or two more and I’ll be doing the first outdoor sowings - parsnips and early peas. Probably the extra early potatoes will also go in the ground. I have a rough plan in my head on what’s going where but will be surprised if soon I won’t be struggling to find space in the raised beds.

• SPINACH & SWEETCORN FINGERS • 

Ingredients 📖 
• Full handful of spinach 🍃 
• 100g of unsalted butter 🧈 
• 1 cup of self raising flour
• 1/4 cup of milk of your choice🥛(I used full fat) 
• 4 heaped tbsp of sweetcorn 🌽 
• 4 eggs 🥚 
• 1 tsp baking powder 
• Handful of grated cheese 🧀
• Long cake tin (you can use any of your choice, round or even cupcake tin 🧁)

Method 👩🏼‍🍳 
1. Using a blender blend the spinach 🍃 and sweetcorn 🌽 till you are happy it’s safe for baby 
2. Add unsalted butter, self raising flour, milk, eggs, baking powder into a big mixing bowl and mix together thoroughly 🥣
3. Add in cheese and mix again 🧀 
4. Add in spinach & sweetcorn and mix again 
5. Either oil the cake tin directly or I used baking paper and oiled that onto the tin and pour mixture into the tin 
6. Cook in oven at 180 degrees for 15-20 mins, keep checking on it 
7. Once cooked wait for it to cool down and cut into little fingers for baby to hold and enjoy 👶🏼❤️

Inspired by @whatmummymakes recipe 

⚠️ Please be with your baby at all times when feeding them this, watching that they do not take a big piece into their mouth as this is a chocking hazard! ⚠️

Let's talk about @flashfoodinc 

If you've been following me for some time than you already know I'm obsessed with this app. Saving money on groceries? Thats right up my alley. 

Most people overlook this app, but it is one app that I cannot live without. 

Let's talk about these photos. In these photos I bought 4 mixed produce boxes. Altogether in these boxes there were: 
• a bag of organic lime 
• 3 bags of clementines 
• a clamshell of guava
• a bag of Lemons
• 3 bags of royal gala apples
• a bag of carrots
• a container of mushrooms 
• 2 packages of red thai peppers
• 1 package of green Thai peppers
• a large clamshell of roma tomatoes

Total retail of all this produce was $74.70.
I only paid $8.00! Which I saved $66.70. 

The best part was I only had to throw out a few clementines, 1 individual apple, 2 individual guava and the carrots i fed to my dads rabbits & chickens. 

Worth. Every. Penny.

captions:
Loving how stocky these tomato seedlings are! 😍. Admittedly these are dwarf tomatoes (Tiny Tim variety) so you'd expect a stockier plant, but even standard tomato seedlings should be as stocky as possible!  
.
.
Stocky tomato plants have a stronger stem which is crucial for supporting the plant as it grows.  A weak tomato will be too fragile to do well outdoors where it will have to contend with windy and exposed conditions. 
.
.
What causes tall and skinny ("leggy") seedlings? The main causes are insufficient light 🌞 or too much crowding 🌱🌱. You can prevent leggy seedlings by ensuring they have enough high quality light right from the start.
.
.
But what about the seedlings you already grew that have turned out to be leggy? Is all hope lost? Nope!  Last year I successfully rescued some leggy tomatoes with the following tricks:
.
1️⃣ Adding more light 💡(either add a grow light, or move to a sunnier location)
.
2️⃣ Ensuring the seedlings are spread out enough so that they aren't competing with each other.  If there are multiple seedlings per pot then pinch out the weakest ones, leaving only the strongest seedling. (Try to avoid disturbing the roots at this stage)
.
3️⃣ Repotting tomatoes and burying the stem up to the first set of leaves.  When a tomato stem is buried it will actually send out roots!  This basically buries the weak part of the stem and let's you try again 🙃 As an added bonus this also increases the root mass - in fact many gardeners do this with all of their tomatoes!
.
4️⃣ Turning on a fan for a little bit each day 💨.  This mimics a natural breeze and will encourage the seedlings to grow stronger stems.  Just don't let them dry out as the fan will increase evaporation!
.
.

Being present is so hard.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Can anyone else relate?⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I read and listen to so many wellness materials like stoicism books, meditations, wellness podcasts, etc. and they all talk about living in the moment and not drifting out of it. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But let me tell you, IT IS HARD. Constant phone notifications, endless scrolls, all of that make it nearly impossible to always be present. But while the scroll can wait, it's important to not miss out on what's right in front of you, because you'll never have another moment like it.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My strategies for being mindful & present? Shut it off & put it away. That's all. Test yourself to do it for 5 minutes. Then another 5. Then another 5. You'll be surprised how easy it becomes to be naturally present and focused.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

It is true that not many people can take the taste of wheatgrass juice, but then I can tell you there are loads of reasons for you not to refuse trying this superfood. 😏

Like at the ripe market, there was a family who came up and asked about wheatgrass and how it is consumed; the husband even wanted to try a shot of it out of curiosity as they are really into healthy and organic foods. 😁😋💪

Well, for some of us who aren’t really fond of our vegetables, it is interesting to know that just 2 ounces of fresh Wheatgrass juice is equivalent to 3 pounds of organic vegetables. Another reason to consider adding Wheatgrass juice to our daily diet. 💛

If you wanna know more, visit https://drmicrogreens.com/high-quality-live-wheatgrass-in-dubai/

💚Lately I was thinking about my journey to plant based / vegan lifestyle..

🤔 I never considered becoming vegan until one day it just happened.. 
 I knew a few people who were vegan, they had dogs or cats, loved their animals more than themselves. 
As I never had any pets, I was convinced that vegan lifestyle is not for me.

Later it came to me that vegan lifestyle is not about being a pet person.
One thing is whether you live with animals (which I still don't see myself doing, but who knows what the future brings) and completely another thing is being against violence and torture.

I might never come close to any animal (e.g. live in the same flat with animals), but what I know for sure - 
I am 100% against the treatment they get in those factories.

🐷Animals deserve a better life.
🌍Nature deserves to flourish.
🙋‍♀️And our body deserves to be nourished.

P. S. I just think, if there is someone out there, who thinks the way I used to think (that you have to be a pet person to adopt the vegan lifestyle) - that person should know = it is not true.

The aroma of this simple thai fried rice is an instant mood lifter!❇️❇️🌼🌼

Ingredients: 

2 cups of cooked basmati rice
1 cup basil leaves
1 small onion, chopped
1/4 cup babycorn
1/4 cup bamboo shoots (optional but add it for the authentic taste)
8-10 Tofu pieces, fried
2 chillies
1/4 cup red bellpepper
1/2 cup blanched brocoli
1 tbsp vegan fish sauce (recipe below)
1 tbsp soy sauce
salt per taste
1 tbsp oil

Recipe for vegan fish sauce :

½ tablespoon chopped garlic about 1 clove
½ tablespoon chili flakes 
½ teaspoon salt
2 tablespoons maple syrup
1 tablespoon lime juice
½ cup [125ml] hot water

Mix everything together in a bowl and store it in a container.

Steps:

1. In a pan, heat oil and add garlic, onions and saute well.
2. Add the bell peppers, bamboo shoots,babycorn and saute till the raw taste is gone.
3. Add the pan fried tofu, broccoli.
4. Add the vegan fish sauce, soy sauce  and the basil leaves and saute for 5 minutes.
5. Add the cooked basmati rice and salt. Mix everything together.
6. Turn off the flame and add the lemon juice and a few basil leaves to finish off.

captions:
How do you feel about sweets?

🍃It was August.  By that time, I had lost 5kg (2 what I had and 3 what I gained while I was changing food) I have a vacation, I leave and stop counting calories.  And so two weeks passed.  I gained 1-1.5 kilograms.  I knew that I had stopped monitoring the diet and it was not surprising to me that I typed.  My weight was below original weight, so I was quite happy.  I just started counting again.

 The weight fluctuated, but I insisted on my own and continued to eat already at 1800 kcal.  I haven't changed anything.  I ate fast food, ate sweets at night, ate various snacks, but everything was within the normal range of calories.  I did not observe proteins, fats and carbohydrates, because the main thing for me was to learn to eat correctly and exactly what I want.  By December, the total weight loss was -8kg.  I was happy.  I began to eat more, I had fewer inhibitions, during this time I allowed myself a lot that I had not allowed before, I finally felt comfortable.

오이미역무침 
Seaweed Salad/ Miyeok Muchim 🥗

Are you carving for a refreshing dish that can boost your appetite? Then this seaweed salad seasoned with sweet & sour gochujang can be a perfect pick 🌟🔥

Super quick and easy to make, a perfect side dish you can eat with your rice, noodles or even with your steak😋

ℹ Korean time 🤗

✔ Miyeok 미역 - seeweed in Korean
✔ Gochujang 고추장 - fermented korwan chilli paste, one of the essential ingredients needed for many korean cooking

🔆 Ingredients
5g dried seaweed, soak in water while prepping, once soften, cut into bite sizes
1/2 continental cucumber, seed with a spoon or knife and thinly slice
1/8 red onion, also thinly slice
1 spring onion, roughly chop or slice
3 garlic, minced or chopped

🥣 seasoning
1.5- 2 tbsp gochujang
1 tbsp sugar
2 tbsp vinegar 
1/2 tbsp sesame oil
1 tbsp sesame seeds

👨‍🍳 how to make
1. Chop/ slice all ingredients like explained 
2. In a mixing bowl, all prepped ingredients + seasoning in, and mix 👋

Seaweed salad is a great vegetarian dish you can show off  as it's super tasty, light, healthy and pretty😍🤩

THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN IRON AND HEMOGLOBIN 👇

Iron is a mineral that the body needs for growth and development. Your body uses iron to make hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen from the lungs to all parts of the body, and myoglobin, a protein that provides oxygen to muscles.

Deficiency in Iron leads to poor oxygen transport (anemia) as well as fatigue, depression, restless leg syndrome to name a few.

It's ideal to get Iron through food. Oysters, meat, chocolate, legumes, and spinach are a few sources.

It's all about balance!

Midweek ramen inspo! This one can come together quite quickly if you pay a visit to your local Asian supermarket ! 

 1) Tare - the flavour bomb that gives flavour and saltiness to your ramen . I used a soy sauce based one which is basically light soy sauce simmered with a splash of mirin and sliced ginger and garlic. 
2) Stock - here I used a veg stock that was made using dried shiitake, kombu, onion, ginger and garlic. But you can use any stock you get your hands on. Note: if your stock is salty, you will have to use less tare to avoid salty mess. 
3) Noodles - shop bough & boiled.
4) Toppings - couple of things I grabbed from my local Asian supermarket. Enoki  mushrooms and pak choi - blanched in hot noodle water to save time. Shop bought gyoza - panfried using fry-steam-fry method. Spring onion - chopped! 

Assembly is super easy - a tbs of tare for a medium size bowl ( I never measure but start low and add more if need to), couple of ladle-fulls of broth. Boiled noodles on top and whatever other toppings you desire ! Happy slurping!

#Homemade Dhokla Platter

#Dhokla ( खट्टा ढोकला /  ખાટ્ટા ઢોકળા )  is a #vegetarian culinary dish that is found mainly in the #Indian state of #Gujarat and parts of adjacent states. It is made with a fermented batter derived from rice and split urad dal. Dhokla can be eaten for #breakfast, as a main course, as a side dish, or as a #snack. 
.
It is very similar to #Khaman, however Dhokla is made of batter derived from mixture of rice and Urad dal, whereas Khaman is typically made from @Chickpeas gram and looks yellow in color. Khaman has become widely popular outside Gujarat but is misunderstood or incorrectly known as Dhokla.
.

Do you know the other names of #𝐏𝐚𝐧𝐢𝐏𝐮𝐫𝐢 in different parts of India?
.
𝐏𝐚𝐧𝐢 𝐏𝐮𝐫𝐢 / पानी पुरी / गोलगप्पे / પાણીપુરી = a round, hollow puri (a deep-fried crisp crepe), filled with a mixture of flavored water (known as imli pani), tamarind chutney, chili, chaat masala, potato, onion, chickpeas or other different fillings in different parts of India

Also known as:
- 𝐆𝐨𝐥 𝐆𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐞 in North India
- 𝐏𝐮𝐜𝐡𝐤𝐚 in West Bengal, Bihar, Jharkhand & Assam
- 𝐏𝐚𝐤𝐨𝐝𝐢 in few parts of Gujarat
- 𝐏𝐚𝐧𝐢 𝐤𝐞 𝐏𝐚𝐭𝐚𝐬𝐡𝐞 in Haryana
- 𝐏𝐚𝐭𝐚𝐬𝐡𝐢 or 𝐏𝐚𝐚𝐧𝐢 𝐤𝐞 𝐁𝐚𝐭𝐚𝐬𝐡𝐞 in some parts of Rajasthan & Uttar Pradesh
- 𝐆𝐮𝐩 𝐂𝐡𝐮𝐩 in Odisha, South Jharkhand, Chhatisgarh, Hyderabad & Telangana
- 𝐏𝐡𝐮𝐥𝐤𝐢 in eastern parts of Uttar Pradesh & even in Nepal
- 𝐅𝐮𝐥𝐤𝐢 in some parts of Madhya Pradesh and
- 𝐖𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐁𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐬 - when simply translated in English (the funniest name of pani puri so far)
.

When you think of a classic cauliflower soup, you think of a soup loaded with cream and thickened with flour. These soups are neither vegan nor very appealing or healthy. 

.
.
.
.

This Creamy Curried Cauliflower Soup has a creamy texture, without adding ingredients that would take away from the cauliflower’s flavor, which is delicate, nutty, and sweet on its own. 
A modest amount of curry powder, sautéed onion, and leek make this soup delicious and healthy. The coconut milk completes the flavor and adds additional flair and creaminess. A splash of olive oil, browned cauliflower florets and fresh scallions give this soup a flavorful garnish. 

.
.
.
.

captions:
Reposted from @plant.based.journey Pulled Pork in Under 20 Min

Super easy… Super Tasty… Super Fast…

What you will need:

20oz. King Oyster Mushrooms per serving (as featured in vid)
tsp. Salt
Pinch Black Pepper
tsp. Garlic Powder
tsp. Smoked Paprika
Favorite BBQ Sauce ( I used @traderjoes KC Style BBQ )
Bun ( I used @daveskillerbread )

After cleaning the mushrooms, gently shred the stalks with a fork beginning just below the cap. You can either save caps for another dish,  or chop up and add to your shreds. The caps will taste fine in your pulled pork, you just won’t have a completely shredded look, if thats what you’re going for.

Add shreds to a pan on medium heat, add all the spices and stir. Cook until tender ( about 10 minutest ) then add your favorite BBQ sauce, and heat to desired eating temp.  At this point its time to put on a bun with your favorite toppings and enjoy. 🤤 or you can eat with your favorite side.

Aubergines are one of my fave veggies, you can do so much with them and they’re like giant sponges that absorb sauces and flavours. We bought some harissa paste a few weeks ago and I’ve been meaning to make something with it as I’ve never actually cooked with it before. I had a left over aubergine to use so I thought I’d combine the two and ended up making this harissa baked aubergine on a bed of couscous. Usually when I make up recipes for the first time, there is something that tastes off or an ingredient that I decide I won’t add next time, but everything in this worked so well together!! I’m writing up the recipe on my blog and will share it on my stories over the next couple of days for anyone who’d like to try making it! It’s almost the weekend woohoo, happy Thursday everyone!!

Baked marinated and stuffed bell peppers
Very good reheated

A take on @howsweeteats recipe

Bell pepper
Mozzarella light
Red vine vinegar 
Garlic
Chili flakes
Salt
Bread
Garlic powder
Olive oil
Butter
Herbs

Drizzle bell pepper with olive oil and bake for 30-35 min at high heat
Whip the marinaded from the garlic, vinegar, salt and olive oil
Take out the peppers and drizzle with the marinates
Tear the bread
Heath some butter in a pan and fry the bread with some garlic powder
Stuff the peppers with mozzarella. 1 ball per serving
Bake a bit if you want the cheese to melt
Top with bread and the marinade
Sprinkle some herbs
Serve

Crunchy sugar coated walnuts 🤤 shout out to @fiozzzna thanks for the recipe! 

Im a little late but Yunjing sent me this recipe for Chinese New Year 🥳 this is a traditional yummy and addictive snack😍

To make🤌
👉2 cups of walnuts 
👉1/4 cup brown sugar 
👉 1/4 teaspoon salt 
👉 1/2 cup water 
👉 pour all ingredients in a pot and stir on medium high heat until all liquid is absorbed 
👉preheat oven to 300 degrees and lay the walnuts on a baking sheet for 20 mins and ENJOY 😍

Harissa Baked Aubergine 🍆 
.
.
Swipe for a video on how I made it! - Aubergines are one of my fave veggies, you can do so much with them and they’re like giant sponges that absorb sauces and flavours. We bought some harissa paste a few weeks ago and I’ve been meaning to make something with it as I’ve never actually cooked with it before. I had a left over aubergine to use so I thought I’d combine the two and ended up making this harissa baked aubergine on a bed of couscous. Usually when I make up recipes for the first time, there is something that tastes off or an ingredient that I decide I won’t add next time, but everything in this worked so well together!! I’m writing up the recipe on my blog and will share it on my stories over the next couple of days for anyone who’d like to try making it! It’s almost the weekend woohoo, happy Thursday everyone!!
